  "doc_id": "53027",
  "text": "The main effects of our research did not vary substantially between genders. That is, for both husbands and wives, self-control and forgiveness were correlated throughout the study, both increased significantly over time, and the developments of self-control and forgiveness were unrelated. In the beginning of marriage, husbands did show higher levels of both self-control and forgiveness compared to wives. Because there was no gender difference in the slopes of these two factors, this difference remained the same over time. This finding is in contrast with previous literature showing that females tend to be more forgiving than men (for a meta-analysis, see [CITATION_1] and generally have a somewhat higher level of self-control (e.g., [CITATION_2] . Future research is needed to examine the robustness of our findings.",
